2026-04-25 | Maximize Minimum Manhattan Distance on Square Boundary

Question
Return the largest possible minimum distance.
	Key Insight
1.	Convert 2D boundary points → 1D positions along perimeter  
2.	Then problem becomes:
		select k points on a circular line  
		maximize minimum distance  
3.	Use:
		Binary Search + Greedy Check  
	Approach
1.	Map each boundary point to perimeter distance:
		if (x==0) → y  
		if (y==side) → side + x  
		if (x==side) → 2*side + (side - y)  
		if (y==0) → 3*side + (side - x)  
2.	Sort positions  
3.	Binary search on answer (distance d)
4.	Check function:
		try to pick k points greedily:
			start from first  
			pick next point ≥ last + d  
5.	Since circular:
		duplicate array with +perimeter  
		and try each starting point  
	Time Complexity
	O(n log n + n log perimeter)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxDistance(int side, vector<vector<int>>& points, int k) {
        vector<int> pos;
        // map to perimeter
        for(auto &p : points){
            int x = p[0], y = p[1];
            if(x == 0) pos.push_back(y);
            else if(y == side) pos.push_back(side + x);
            else if(x == side) pos.push_back(2*side + (side - y));
            else pos.push_back(3*side + (side - x));
        }
        sort(pos.begin(), pos.end());
        int n = pos.size();
        int perimeter = 4 * side;
        // extend for circular handling
        vector<int> ext = pos;
        for(int x : pos){
            ext.push_back(x + perimeter);
        }
        auto can = [&](int d){
            for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
                int count = 1;
                int last = ext[i];
                for(int j = i + 1; j < i + n; j++){
                    if(ext[j] - last >= d){
                        count++;
                        last = ext[j];
                    }
                    if(count >= k) return true;
                }
            }
            return false;
        };
        int low = 0, high = perimeter, ans = 0;
        while(low <= high){
            int mid = (low + high) / 2;
            if(can(mid)){
                ans = mid;
                low = mid + 1;
            } else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
This is a classic pattern:
		“maximize minimum distance” → binary search  
Key trick:
		convert 2D boundary → 1D circular line  
This simplifies geometry into a linear greedy problem.
